---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base
  title="Alpenglow"
  description="Alpenglow is a musl Linux distribution with an immutable RAM-loaded root image and persistent bcachefs-backed state."
>
  <main class="page">
    <h1>Alpenglow</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      A general-purpose Linux distribution built around a diskless boot model: the system image is loaded into
      memory at startup, while user data and package state persist on disk under <code>/state</code>.
    </p>

    <div class="cta-row">
      <a class="button primary" href="/demo/">Try the in-browser demo</a>
      <a class="button" href="https://github.com/tschk/alpenglow">Repository</a>
    </div>

    <section id="model">
      <h2>Immutable root, persistent state</h2>
      <p>
        Alpenglow separates the replaceable operating system from durable machine state. The root filesystem is
        delivered as an erofs or squashfs image in the initramfs and mounted read-only in RAM. Home directories,
        package metadata, logs, and caches live outside that image on bcachefs-backed storage, then bind into the
        running system.
      </p>
      <p>
        Updates are image swaps: build a new root image, boot it, and keep user data and Oil state intact.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="stack">
      <h2>Stack</h2>

      <h3>dinit</h3>
      <p>
        Service supervision uses a parallel dependency graph. Init brings up networking, persistence mounts, and
        profile-selected daemons without a heavyweight default target tree.
      </p>

      <h3>Oil</h3>
      <p>
        Oil is Alpenglow&apos;s native package manager. It speaks APK-compatible metadata, keeps install state under
        <code>/state</code>, and installs into the mutable layer without baking packages into the immutable root
        image.
      </p>

      <h3>Alpenglowed</h3>
      <p>
        The desktop profile adds Wayland via <a href="https://github.com/tschk/alpenglowed">Alpenglowed</a> (Smithay),
        greetd, seatd, PipeWire, and foot on the same immutable root model—not a separate root-on-disk distribution.
      </p>

      <h3>Kernel policy</h3>
      <p>
        Small Zig helpers (<code>kernelctl</code>, <code>netd</code>, zram and pressure tooling) enforce cgroup
        policy, network state, and resource limits with static binaries suitable for initramfs use.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="profiles">
      <h2>Profiles</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>minimal</strong> — headless appliance: SSH, time sync, logging, DNS, OOM guard.</li>
        <li><strong>standard</strong> — minimal plus compiler tooling, network utilities, and filesystem tools.</li>
        <li><strong>desktop</strong> — standard plus graphics, audio, Wi‑Fi, greetd, Alpenglowed, and foot.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Kernel profiles (<code>fast</code>, <code>minimal</code>, <code>desktop</code>) select hardware and boot
        policy independently of the userspace image.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="platforms">
      <h2>Platforms</h2>
      <p>
        Primary targets are x86_64 and aarch64, with QEMU and real-hardware bring-up (including Orange Pi 3B and Mac
        mini 2012). The public demo is a 32-bit Alpenglow minimal initramfs (toybox, dinit, Oil) in v86—not a third-party
        distro rootfs. Production images use the full musl appliance build.
      </p>
    </section>
  </main>
</Base>